slides_data.notes: Hi there! This is a quick byte on Conditionals.
☑️ Do This: Explain that the word "if" tells the computer to check something – a condition – and only run the next steps if that condition is true.
☑️ Do This: Explain that this is the condition. If it is true, then the steps that follow will run.
☑️ Do This: Explain that the colon tells Python that the next indented lines are part of the if block.
☑️ Do This: Explain that these lines will only run if the condition is true.
☑️ Do This: Remind students that indentation is important in Python. Emphasize that if these lines weren't indented, they would always run, even if the condition were false.

scenes.speech: Hi there! This is a quick byte on Conditionals.
scenes.elevenlabs: [American accent] [warmly welcoming] Hi there! This is a quick byte on Conditionals.

scenes.comment: Scene 2: Definition of a Conditional Statement.
scenes.speech: So, what exactly is a conditional statement? It tells your computer to do something only if a certain condition is true. Think of it like a decision point in your code.
scenes.elevenlabs: [thoughtful] So, what exactly is a conditional statement? [patiently] It tells your computer to do something only if a certain condition is true. Think of it like a decision point in your code.

scenes.speech: In Python, we use the word 'if' to tell the computer to check something - a condition. The steps that follow will only run if that condition is true.
scenes.elevenlabs: [clearly] In Python, we use the word 'if' to tell the computer to check something - a condition. [emphasized] The steps that follow will only run if that condition is true.

scenes.speech: This part, 'isabel dot can move south', is our condition. The program will check if Isabel can move south. If this is true, then the steps that come next will run.
scenes.elevenlabs: [patiently] This part, 'isabel dot can move south', is our condition. [deliberate] The program will check if Isabel can move south. If this is true, then the steps that come next will run.

scenes.speech: Notice the colon after the condition. This colon tells Python that the next indented lines are part of this 'if' block.
scenes.elevenlabs: [emphasized] Notice the colon after the condition. [clearly] This colon tells Python that the next indented lines are part of this 'if' block.

scenes.comment: Scene 6: Explaining that lines run only if the condition is true.
scenes.speech: These two lines, 'isabel dot move' and 'isabel dot paint blue', are indented. This means they are connected to our 'if' statement. They will only run if the condition is true.
scenes.elevenlabs: [deliberate] These two lines, 'isabel dot move' and 'isabel dot paint blue', are indented. This means they are connected to our 'if' statement. [stressed] They will only run if the condition is TRUE.

scenes.comment: Scene 7: Emphasizing the importance of indentation.
scenes.speech: Indentation is super important in Python! If these lines weren't indented, they wouldn't be part of the 'if' block and would always run, no matter if Isabel could move south or not.
scenes.elevenlabs: [excited] Indentation is super important in Python! [short pause] If these lines weren't indented, they wouldn't be part of the 'if' block and would always run, no matter if Isabel could move south or not.
